-- ── TRACK 10: AUTH & SECURITY ────────────────────────────

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# JWT — JSON Web Tokens Explained\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nJWT (JSON Web Token) is the most common authentication mechanism in modern APIs. Unlike sessions (which store state on the server), JWTs are self-contained — the token itself contains all the information needed to verify the user''s identity.\n\nEvery time you use a mobile app, a React SPA, or a microservices API, JWTs are likely being used behind the scenes.\n\n---\n\n## 2. JWT Structure\n\n```\nA JWT is three Base64URL-encoded sections separated by dots:\n\neyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9\n.eyJzdWIiOiJ1c2VyLTEyMyIsIm5hbWUiOiJBbGljZSIsInJvbGUiOiJlbXBsb3llZSIsImlhdCI6MTcwNDcwMDAwMCwiZXhwIjoxNzA0NzAzNjAwfQ\n.SflKxwRJSMeKKF2QT4fwpMeJf36POk6yJV_adQssw5c\n\nPart 1 — HEADER (algorithm)\n{ "alg": "HS256", "typ": "JWT" }\n\nPart 2 — PAYLOAD (claims)\n{\n  "sub":  "user-123",       // Subject (user ID)\n  "name": "Alice Sharma",\n  "role": "employee",\n  "dept": "Engineering",\n  "iat":  1704700000,       // Issued at (Unix timestamp)\n  "exp":  1704703600,       // Expires at (1 hour later)\n  "iss":  "rlearn.com",    // Issuer\n  "aud":  "rlearn-api"     // Audience\n}\n\nPart 3 — SIGNATURE\nHMACSHA256(\n  base64url(header) + "." + base64url(payload),\n  SECRET_KEY\n)\n```\n\n## 3. Creating & Verifying JWTs\n\n```typescript\nimport jwt from "jsonwebtoken";\n\nconst SECRET_KEY = process.env.JWT_SECRET!;\n\n// Generate token after successful login\nfunction generateToken(user: User): string {\n  return jwt.sign(\n    {\n      sub:  user.id,\n      name: user.name,\n      role: user.role,\n      dept: user.department,\n    },\n    SECRET_KEY,\n    {\n      expiresIn: "1h",     // Access token: short-lived\n      issuer:    "rlearn.com",\n      audience:  "rlearn-api",\n    }\n  );\n}\n\nfunction generateRefreshToken(userId: string): string {\n  return jwt.sign(\n    { sub: userId, type: "refresh" },\n    process.env.JWT_REFRESH_SECRET!,\n    { expiresIn: "30d" } // Refresh token: long-lived\n  );\n}\n\n// Verify token in middleware\nfunction verifyToken(token: string): JwtPayload {\n  try {\n    return jwt.verify(token, SECRET_KEY, {\n      issuer:   "rlearn.com",\n      audience: "rlearn-api",\n    }) as JwtPayload;\n  } catch (err) {\n    if (err instanceof jwt.TokenExpiredError) {\n      throw new AuthError("Token expired", "TOKEN_EXPIRED");\n    }\n    if (err instanceof jwt.JsonWebTokenError) {\n      throw new AuthError("Invalid token", "INVALID_TOKEN");\n    }\n    throw err;\n  }\n}\n\n// Express middleware\nexport async function authenticate(req, res, next) {\n  const header = req.headers.authorization;\n  if (!header?.startsWith("Bearer ")) {\n    return res.status(401).json({ error: "No token" });\n  }\n\n  try {\n    const payload = verifyToken(header.split(" ")[1]);\n    req.user = { id: payload.sub, role: payload.role };\n    next();\n  } catch (err) {\n    if (err.code === "TOKEN_EXPIRED") {\n      return res.status(401).json({ error: "Token expired", code: "TOKEN_EXPIRED" });\n    }\n    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid token" });\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## 4. Security Best Practices\n\n```\n✅ JWT Security Checklist:\n\n1. Strong Secret Key\n   - Minimum 256 bits (32+ characters)\n   - Store in environment variable, never in code\n   - Different secrets for access and refresh tokens\n   SECRET_KEY = node -e "console.log(require(''crypto'').randomBytes(64).toString(''hex''))"\n\n2. Short Expiry for Access Tokens\n   - Access token: 15 minutes to 1 hour\n   - Refresh token: 7-30 days\n   - Reason: if stolen, impact is limited to short window\n\n3. HTTPS Only\n   - Never send tokens over HTTP\n   - Tokens intercepted over HTTP are as good as stolen\n\n4. Token Storage\n   - Web apps: httpOnly cookie (preferred) or memory\n   - Avoid localStorage: vulnerable to XSS attacks\n   - httpOnly cookie: not accessible to JavaScript\n\n5. Validate All Claims\n   - Check exp (expiry)\n   - Check iss (issuer)\n   - Check aud (audience)\n   - Reject tokens with unexpected claims\n\n6. Refresh Token Rotation\n   - Issue new refresh token on every use\n   - Revoke old refresh token immediately\n   - Detect reuse (if old token used, invalidate all)\n\n7. Token Revocation\n   - JWTs are stateless — they can''t be "invalidated" on server\n   - Maintain a revocation list (Redis) for emergency cases\n   - Or use short expiry + refresh token rotation\n\n❌ Common JWT Mistakes:\n- Using "none" algorithm (allows forged tokens)\n- Storing sensitive data in payload (it''s readable!)\n- Long expiry times (30 days for access tokens)\n- Storing in localStorage\n- Not validating signature algorithm type\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between authentication and authorization?**\n> Authentication: verifying WHO you are (login — prove your identity). Authorization: determining WHAT you can do (access control — do you have permission?). JWT handles authentication — it proves the request comes from a specific user. Role-based access control (RBAC) handles authorization — checks if that user has the required role/permission.\n\n**Q: What are the advantages and disadvantages of JWTs?**\n> Advantages: Stateless (no server-side storage), self-contained (all info in token), works across domains/microservices, no session store needed. Disadvantages: Cannot be invalidated before expiry (stateless), payload is readable (Base64), larger than session IDs, secret key management is critical. Best for APIs and microservices; sessions may be better for monolithic web apps.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What are the three parts of a JWT?\n2. What does the signature verify?\n3. Why should access tokens have short expiry?\n4. Why is `localStorage` not safe for storing JWTs?\n5. What is a refresh token?\n6. Can you invalidate a JWT before it expires?\n7. What is the `sub` claim?\n8. What is token refresh rotation?\n9. What algorithm is HS256?\n10. What is the difference between JWT and sessions?\n\n---\n\n## 7. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| JWT Structure | Header.Payload.Signature |\n| Payload | Contains claims — NOT secrets |\n| Signature | Verifies token wasn''t tampered |\n| Access token | Short-lived (15min-1hr) |\n| Refresh token | Long-lived (7-30 days) |\n| httpOnly cookie | Secure storage — JS can''t read |\n| Never in localStorage | Vulnerable to XSS |\n\nJWT is the currency of modern API authentication. Handle tokens like passwords: strong keys, short expiry, HTTPS only, secure storage.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l100401';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# OWASP Top 10 — The Most Critical Web Security Risks\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nThe OWASP (Open Web Application Security Project) Top 10 is the industry-standard reference for web application security risks. Every professional developer must understand these vulnerabilities — not just to prevent them but because security issues in your code can result in data breaches, legal liability, and destroyed user trust.\n\n---\n\n## 2. OWASP Top 10 (2021)\n\n```\nA01: Broken Access Control\nA02: Cryptographic Failures\nA03: Injection (SQL, NoSQL, LDAP, Command)\nA04: Insecure Design\nA05: Security Misconfiguration\nA06: Vulnerable and Outdated Components\nA07: Identification and Authentication Failures\nA08: Software and Data Integrity Failures\nA09: Security Logging and Monitoring Failures\nA10: Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)\n```\n\n## 3. SQL Injection\n\n```typescript\n// ❌ VULNERABLE — string concatenation\nconst userId = req.params.id; // Attacker sends: "1; DROP TABLE users; --"\nconst query = `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ${userId}`;\n// Result: SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = 1; DROP TABLE users; --\n\n// ✅ SAFE — parameterized queries (placeholders)\nimport { pool } from "./db";\n\n// PostgreSQL — $1, $2 placeholders\nconst { rows } = await pool.query(\n  "SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1",\n  [userId]  // Escaped and sanitized automatically\n);\n\n// Supabase\nconst { data } = await supabase\n  .from("users")\n  .select("*")\n  .eq("id", userId); // Always parameterized\n\n// NEVER use string interpolation in queries!\n// ALWAYS use parameterized queries or ORMs\n```\n\n## 4. XSS — Cross-Site Scripting\n\n```typescript\n// ❌ VULNERABLE\nfunction displayComment(comment: string) {\n  container.innerHTML = comment;\n  // If comment = ''<script>document.cookie = "stolen=" + document.cookie</script>''\n  // Attacker steals session!\n}\n\n// ✅ SAFE — always escape user content\nfunction displayComment(comment: string) {\n  const p = document.createElement("p");\n  p.textContent = comment;  // Escapes HTML entities\n  container.appendChild(p);\n}\n\n// React automatically escapes: safe by default\n// {userContent}  → escaped and safe\n// dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: userContent }}  → DANGEROUS\n\n// Content Security Policy header\napp.use(helmet.contentSecurityPolicy({\n  directives: {\n    defaultSrc: ["''self''"],\n    scriptSrc:  ["''self''"],  // No inline scripts\n    styleSrc:   ["''self''", "''unsafe-inline''"], // For CSS-in-JS\n    imgSrc:     ["''self''", "data:", "https:"],\n  },\n}));\n```\n\n## 5. CSRF — Cross-Site Request Forgery\n\n```typescript\n// Attack: Malicious site tricks user''s browser into making authenticated requests\n// <img src="https://bank.com/transfer?to=attacker&amount=10000">\n// Browser sends cookies automatically → authenticated request!\n\n// Defense 1: SameSite cookies\nres.cookie("session", token, {\n  httpOnly: true,\n  secure:   true,\n  sameSite: "strict",  // Cookie only sent from same site\n});\n\n// Defense 2: CSRF tokens\nimport csurf from "csurf";\napp.use(csurf({ cookie: true }));\n\n// In form:\nres.render("form", { csrfToken: req.csrfToken() });\n// <input type="hidden" name="_csrf" value="<%= csrfToken %>"/>\n\n// Defense 3: Check Origin/Referer headers\napp.use((req, res, next) => {\n  const origin = req.headers.origin;\n  if (!origin || !allowedOrigins.includes(origin)) {\n    return res.status(403).json({ error: "Forbidden" });\n  }\n  next();\n});\n```\n\n## 6. Input Validation & Sanitization\n\n```typescript\nimport { z } from "zod";\n\n// Schema validation with Zod\nconst CreateCourseSchema = z.object({\n  title: z.string()\n    .min(3, "Title too short")\n    .max(100, "Title too long")\n    .trim(),\n  description: z.string().max(2000).optional(),\n  level: z.enum(["Beginner", "Intermediate", "Advanced"]),\n  category: z.string().min(1),\n  price: z.number().min(0).max(100000),\n});\n\nrouter.post("/courses", authenticate, async (req, res, next) => {\n  const result = CreateCourseSchema.safeParse(req.body);\n\n  if (!result.success) {\n    return res.status(422).json({\n      error: "Validation failed",\n      details: result.error.flatten().fieldErrors,\n    });\n  }\n\n  const course = await CourseService.create(result.data); // Safe data\n  res.status(201).json({ data: course });\n});\n\n// Sanitize HTML content (for rich text editors)\nimport DOMPurify from "dompurify";\nimport { JSDOM } from "jsdom";\n\nconst window = new JSDOM("").window;\nconst purify = DOMPurify(window);\n\nfunction sanitizeHtml(dirty: string): string {\n  return purify.sanitize(dirty, {\n    ALLOWED_TAGS: ["b", "i", "em", "strong", "a", "p", "br", "ul", "li"],\n    ALLOWED_ATTR: ["href"],\n  });\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between XSS and CSRF?**\n> XSS (Cross-Site Scripting): Attacker injects malicious script into your page that runs in other users'' browsers. Attacker exploits your site. CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery): Malicious site tricks a user''s browser into making authenticated requests to your API using their cookies. Attacker exploits the user''s authenticated session. XSS defense: escape output, CSP. CSRF defense: SameSite cookies, CSRF tokens.\n\n**Q: Why is parameterized query safer than string concatenation for SQL?**\n> With string concatenation, user input becomes part of the SQL structure — malicious input can change query logic (`OR 1=1 --`). With parameterized queries, user input is always treated as DATA, never SQL code. The database driver handles escaping. Even if input contains SQL syntax, it is treated as a literal string value, not executable SQL.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What is SQL injection and how do you prevent it?\n2. What is XSS and what is the safest way to display user content?\n3. What is CSRF and how do SameSite cookies help?\n4. What does `httpOnly` on a cookie do?\n5. Why is input validation important even if the frontend validates?\n6. What is the Content Security Policy header?\n7. What is broken access control?\n8. Why should error messages not reveal implementation details?\n9. What is the principle of least privilege?\n10. What is HTTPS and why is it required for security?\n\n---\n\n## 9. Lesson Summary\n\n| Attack | Prevention |\n|--------|------------|\n| SQL Injection | Parameterized queries |\n| XSS | Escape output, CSP header |\n| CSRF | SameSite cookies, CSRF tokens |\n| Data exposure | Encrypt at rest and transit |\n| Broken auth | Strong passwords, MFA, short token expiry |\n| Bad validation | Server-side validation always |\n\nSecurity is not a feature — it is a property of how you build. Every input is hostile until proven safe. Every output must be escaped. Defense in depth: validate at every layer, encode all output, use principle of least privilege.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l100901';

-- ── TRACK 11: DATABASE FUNDAMENTALS ──────────────────────

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# SQL Basics — SELECT & Filtering\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nSQL (Structured Query Language) is the language of relational databases. It is used by PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite, and countless other systems. Learning SQL means you can work with data at any company, in any role — developer, analyst, or engineer.\n\nThe `SELECT` statement is the foundation — it retrieves data from tables. Master it and you master most of what you need for day-to-day database work.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SELECT Fundamentals\n\n```sql\n-- Select all columns\nSELECT * FROM users;\n\n-- Select specific columns\nSELECT id, email, full_name, department FROM users;\n\n-- Aliases\nSELECT\n  id            AS user_id,\n  full_name     AS name,\n  department    AS dept,\n  created_at    AS joined\nFROM users;\n\n-- Distinct values\nSELECT DISTINCT department FROM users;\nSELECT DISTINCT level FROM courses;\n\n-- Computed columns\nSELECT\n  title,\n  duration_hours,\n  duration_hours * 60 AS duration_minutes,\n  UPPER(title) AS title_upper,\n  LENGTH(title) AS title_length\nFROM courses;\n\n-- Ordering results\nSELECT * FROM courses ORDER BY title;              -- Default: ASC\nSELECT * FROM courses ORDER BY enrolled DESC;      -- Descending\nSELECT * FROM courses ORDER BY level, enrolled DESC; -- Multi-column\n\n-- Limiting results\nSELECT * FROM courses LIMIT 10;\nSELECT * FROM courses LIMIT 10 OFFSET 20;  -- Skip first 20 (page 3)\n\n-- Pagination formula\n-- Page N, limit L: OFFSET = (N-1) * L\nSELECT * FROM courses ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT 20 OFFSET 40; -- Page 3\n```\n\n## 3. WHERE Clause — Filtering\n\n```sql\n-- Comparison operators\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE role = ''admin'';\nSELECT * FROM courses WHERE duration_hours > 10;\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE xp >= 1000;\nSELECT * FROM courses WHERE is_published = true;\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE bio IS NULL;\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE bio IS NOT NULL;\n\n-- Logical operators\nSELECT * FROM courses\nWHERE level = ''Beginner'' AND category = ''Frontend'';\n\nSELECT * FROM users\nWHERE role = ''admin'' OR role = ''mentor'';\n\nSELECT * FROM courses\nWHERE NOT (level = ''Advanced'');\n\n-- IN — match any in list\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE department IN (''Engineering'', ''Design'', ''Product'');\nSELECT * FROM courses WHERE id IN (''c1'', ''c2'', ''c3'');\n\n-- BETWEEN — inclusive range\nSELECT * FROM courses WHERE duration_hours BETWEEN 5 AND 20;\nSELECT * FROM users WHERE created_at BETWEEN ''2024-01-01'' AND ''2024-12-31'';\n\n-- LIKE — pattern matching\nSELECT * FROM courses WHERE title LIKE ''%JavaScript%'';  -- Contains\nSELECT * FROM users  WHERE email LIKE ''%@rlearn.com'';   -- Ends with\nSELECT * FROM courses WHERE title LIKE ''React%'';        -- Starts with\nSELECT * FROM users  WHERE full_name ILIKE ''alice%'';    -- Case-insensitive (PostgreSQL)\n\n-- Subquery in WHERE\nSELECT * FROM users\nWHERE id IN (\n  SELECT DISTINCT user_id FROM user_progress\n);\n-- Users who have completed at least one lesson\n```\n\n## 4. SQL Functions\n\n```sql\n-- String functions\nSELECT UPPER(full_name) FROM users;\nSELECT LOWER(email) FROM users;\nSELECT LENGTH(title) FROM courses;\nSELECT TRIM(''  hello  '');           -- "hello"\nSELECT SUBSTRING(email, 1, 10);      -- First 10 chars\nSELECT CONCAT(first_name, '' '', last_name) AS full_name;\nSELECT REPLACE(title, ''JS'', ''JavaScript'');\nSELECT SPLIT_PART(email, ''@'', 1) AS username; -- PostgreSQL\n\n-- Numeric functions\nSELECT ROUND(4.567, 2);   -- 4.57\nSELECT CEIL(4.1);          -- 5\nSELECT FLOOR(4.9);         -- 4\nSELECT ABS(-15);            -- 15\nSELECT MOD(10, 3);          -- 1\nSELECT POWER(2, 8);         -- 256\n\n-- Date functions (PostgreSQL)\nSELECT NOW();                                -- Current timestamp\nSELECT CURRENT_DATE;                         -- Today''s date\nSELECT DATE_PART(''year'', created_at);       -- Extract year\nSELECT AGE(NOW(), created_at) AS account_age;\nSELECT TO_CHAR(created_at, ''YYYY-MM-DD'');   -- Format date\nSELECT created_at + INTERVAL ''30 days'';     -- Add 30 days\n\n-- Conditional functions\nSELECT\n  full_name,\n  CASE\n    WHEN xp >= 5000 THEN ''Expert''\n    WHEN xp >= 2000 THEN ''Advanced''\n    WHEN xp >= 500  THEN ''Intermediate''\n    ELSE ''Beginner''\n  END AS level\nFROM users;\n\nSELECT COALESCE(bio, ''No bio yet'') AS bio FROM users;\nSELECT NULLIF(department, ''Unassigned'') FROM users;\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Aggregate Functions\n\n```sql\n-- COUNT, SUM, AVG, MIN, MAX\nSELECT COUNT(*) AS total_users FROM users;\nSELECT COUNT(*) FROM users WHERE role = ''admin'';\nSELECT SUM(xp) AS total_xp FROM users;\nSELECT AVG(xp)::INTEGER AS avg_xp FROM users;\nSELECT MIN(xp), MAX(xp) FROM users;\nSELECT COUNT(DISTINCT department) AS dept_count FROM users;\n\n-- GROUP BY — aggregate by category\nSELECT department, COUNT(*) AS user_count, AVG(xp)::INTEGER AS avg_xp\nFROM users\nGROUP BY department\nORDER BY user_count DESC;\n\n-- HAVING — filter after aggregation (WHERE filters rows, HAVING filters groups)\nSELECT department, COUNT(*) AS user_count\nFROM users\nGROUP BY department\nHAVING COUNT(*) > 5     -- Only departments with more than 5 users\nORDER BY user_count DESC;\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between WHERE and HAVING?**\n> WHERE filters individual rows BEFORE grouping. HAVING filters groups AFTER GROUP BY. You cannot use aggregate functions (COUNT, SUM, AVG) in WHERE — use HAVING for that. Example: `WHERE xp > 100` filters individual users; `HAVING COUNT(*) > 5` filters after grouping.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `COUNT(*)` and `COUNT(column_name)`?**\n> `COUNT(*)` counts ALL rows including those with NULLs. `COUNT(column_name)` counts only rows where that column is NOT NULL. For checking if rows exist, use `COUNT(*)`; for counting non-null values in a column, use `COUNT(column_name)`.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. How do you select only unique values?\n2. What does `ILIKE` do?\n3. What is `BETWEEN` used for?\n4. What is the difference between WHERE and HAVING?\n5. How do you paginate results?\n6. What does `COALESCE` do?\n7. What is `GROUP BY` used for?\n8. How do you sort in descending order?\n9. What does `IN` operator do?\n10. What is the difference between `COUNT(*)` and `COUNT(column)`?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Syntax |\n|---------|--------|\n| Select all | `SELECT * FROM table` |\n| Filter | `WHERE condition` |\n| Sort | `ORDER BY col [DESC]` |\n| Limit | `LIMIT n OFFSET skip` |\n| Match list | `col IN (a, b, c)` |\n| Pattern | `col LIKE ''%text%''` |\n| Aggregate | `COUNT(*), SUM, AVG, MIN, MAX` |\n| Group | `GROUP BY col` |\n| Filter groups | `HAVING condition` |\n\nSQL is the universal language of data. Whether you work in frontend, backend, or data engineering, being able to query a database confidently is a skill that pays dividends throughout your career.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l110201';

-- ── TRACK 12: GIT & GITHUB ───────────────────────────────

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Git Fundamentals — Version Control Mastery\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nGit is the most important developer tool after your code editor. It tracks every change to your code, enables collaboration without overwriting each other''s work, and lets you travel back in time to any previous state of your project.\n\nEvery professional development team uses Git. Not knowing it is not an option.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Core Concepts\n\n```\nGit''s Three Areas:\n\nWorking Directory → Staging Area → Repository (.git folder)\n\nWorking Directory: Your files on disk (what you edit)\nStaging Area: What will go into the next commit (index)\nRepository: Git''s database of all commits and history\n\nFlow:\n1. Edit files (Working Directory)\n2. Stage changes: git add\n3. Commit: git commit (saves snapshot to repository)\n\nRepository structure:\n  .git/\n    HEAD           ← Which branch you''re on\n    index          ← Staging area\n    objects/       ← All blobs, trees, commits\n    refs/heads/    ← Branch pointers\n    refs/remotes/  ← Remote branch pointers\n```\n\n## 3. Essential Commands\n\n```bash\n# === SETUP ===\ngit config --global user.name "Alice Sharma"\ngit config --global user.email "alice@rlearn.com"\ngit config --global core.editor "code --wait"\ngit config --global init.defaultBranch main\n\n# === REPOSITORY ===\ngit init                      # Create new repo in current directory\ngit clone <url>               # Clone remote repo\ngit clone <url> folder-name   # Clone into specific folder\n\n# === STATUS & HISTORY ===\ngit status                    # What''s changed?\ngit log                       # Full commit history\ngit log --oneline             # Compact history\ngit log --oneline --graph --all # Visual branch graph\ngit log -p                    # Commits + diffs\ngit log --author="Alice"      # Commits by author\ngit show <commit-hash>        # Show specific commit\ngit diff                      # Unstaged changes\ngit diff --staged             # Staged changes\ngit diff main..feature        # Diff between branches\n\n# === STAGING & COMMITTING ===\ngit add filename.ts           # Stage specific file\ngit add src/                  # Stage directory\ngit add .                     # Stage all changes\ngit add -p                    # Interactive staging (hunk by hunk)\ngit commit -m "feat: add user authentication"\ngit commit --amend            # Modify last commit (message or files)\n                              # NEVER amend pushed commits!\n\n# === BRANCHING ===\ngit branch                    # List local branches\ngit branch -a                 # List all branches (including remote)\ngit branch feature/auth       # Create branch\ngit checkout feature/auth     # Switch to branch\ngit checkout -b feature/auth  # Create and switch\ngit switch feature/auth       # Modern checkout syntax\ngit switch -c feature/auth    # Create and switch (modern)\ngit branch -d feature/auth    # Delete merged branch\ngit branch -D feature/auth    # Force delete\n\n# === MERGING & REBASING ===\ngit merge feature/auth        # Merge into current branch\ngit merge --no-ff feature/auth # Always create merge commit\ngit rebase main               # Rebase current branch onto main\ngit rebase --abort            # Abort in-progress rebase\ngit cherry-pick <hash>        # Apply specific commit to current branch\n\n# === REMOTE ===\ngit remote -v                 # Show remotes\ngit remote add origin <url>   # Add remote\ngit push origin main          # Push to remote\ngit push -u origin feature    # Push + set upstream\ngit pull                      # Fetch + merge\ngit fetch                     # Fetch without merging\n\n# === UNDO ===\ngit restore filename.ts       # Discard working dir changes\ngit restore --staged filename # Unstage file\ngit reset HEAD~1              # Undo last commit (keep changes staged)\ngit reset --soft HEAD~1       # Undo commit, keep changes staged\ngit reset --hard HEAD~1       # DANGEROUS: Undo commit + discard changes\ngit revert <hash>             # Create new commit that undoes changes\n```\n\n## 4. Git Commit Conventions\n\n```bash\n# Conventional Commits (industry standard)\n# type(scope): description\n\n# Types:\nfeat:     # New feature\nfix:      # Bug fix\ndocs:     # Documentation\nstyle:    # Formatting (no logic change)\nrefactor: # Code restructuring (no logic change)\ntest:     # Adding or fixing tests\nchore:    # Build tools, deps, config\nperf:     # Performance improvement\nrevert:   # Revert previous commit\n\n# Examples:\ngit commit -m "feat(auth): add JWT refresh token endpoint"\ngit commit -m "fix(courses): prevent duplicate enrollment"\ngit commit -m "docs(api): update authentication documentation"\ngit commit -m "refactor(db): extract query builders to repository layer"\ngit commit -m "test(auth): add integration tests for login flow"\n\n# Multi-line commit messages\ngit commit -m "feat(courses): add module completion tracking\n\nUsers can now mark modules as complete. Progress is persisted to\nthe database and shown on the course detail page.\n\nCloses #123"\n```\n\n## 5. .gitignore\n\n```gitignore\n# Node.js\nnode_modules/\nnpm-debug.log*\nyarn-error.log*\n.pnp\n\n# Build output\ndist/\nbuild/\n.next/\n.cache/\n\n# Environment variables (NEVER commit!)\n.env\n.env.local\n.env.*.local\n\n# IDE\n.vscode/settings.json\n.idea/\n*.swp\n*.swo\n\n# OS\n.DS_Store\nThumbs.db\n\n# TypeScript\n*.tsbuildinfo\n\n# Testing\ncoverage/\n.nyc_output\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `git rebase` and `git merge`?**\n> Both integrate changes from one branch to another. `merge` creates a new merge commit preserving the branch history — non-destructive, parallel history visible. `rebase` moves commits from one branch onto another, rewriting them — creates linear history, cleaner log, but rewrites history. Use merge for feature branches going to main (preserves context); use rebase to clean up local work before pushing (linear history).\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `git reset` and `git revert`?**\n> `reset` moves the branch pointer backward, potentially destroying commits — dangerous if commits are already pushed. `revert` creates a NEW commit that undoes the changes — safe because it doesn''t rewrite history. Use `revert` for undoing pushed commits; use `reset` only for local-only commits.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What are the three areas in Git?\n2. What does `git add` do?\n3. What is the difference between `git fetch` and `git pull`?\n4. How do you create and switch to a branch?\n5. What is the difference between merge and rebase?\n6. Why should you never amend pushed commits?\n7. What is `.gitignore` used for?\n8. What does `git stash` do?\n9. What is `HEAD` in Git?\n10. What is the conventional commits format?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---------|--------|\n| `git add` | Stage changes |\n| `git commit` | Save snapshot |\n| `git branch` | Manage branches |\n| `git merge` | Combine branches |\n| `git push/pull` | Sync with remote |\n| `git revert` | Undo safely |\n| `git log --oneline` | View history |\n\nGit mastery is a superpower. Version control enables fearless development — you can always go back. Commit often, write meaningful messages, and never commit secrets.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l120101';

-- ── TRACK 13: BACKEND ARCHITECTURE ───────────────────────

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Layered Architecture — Organizing Backend Code\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nAs applications grow, putting all logic in route handlers creates an unmaintainable mess — business logic mixed with database code, mixed with HTTP handling. Layered architecture separates these concerns into distinct layers, each with a clear responsibility.\n\nThis is the architecture used at scale by virtually every professional backend team.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The Layers\n\n```\nHTTP Layer (Routes/Controllers)\n    ↓  HTTP request in, HTTP response out\nService Layer (Business Logic)\n    ↓  Orchestrates use cases\nRepository Layer (Data Access)\n    ↓  Database queries\nDatabase\n\nRules:\n- Each layer only knows about the layer DIRECTLY below it\n- No HTTP types (req/res) below the Controller layer\n- No database types above the Repository layer\n- Business logic lives in Services, NEVER in Controllers or Repositories\n```\n\n## 3. Implementation Example\n\n```typescript\n// ====== types.ts — Shared interfaces ======\ninterface Course {\n  id:          string;\n  title:       string;\n  level:       "Beginner" | "Intermediate" | "Advanced";\n  authorId:    string;\n  publishedAt: Date | null;\n}\n\ninterface CreateCourseDTO {\n  title:       string;\n  level:       "Beginner" | "Intermediate" | "Advanced";\n  description?: string;\n}\n\ninterface CoursePaginationOptions {\n  page:     number;\n  limit:    number;\n  category?: string;\n  level?:   string;\n}\n\n// ====== repositories/course.repository.ts ======\n// ONLY database logic — no business rules\n\nexport class CourseRepository {\n  async findAll(opts: CoursePaginationOptions): Promise<{ courses: Course[]; total: number }> {\n    const offset = (opts.page - 1) * opts.limit;\n    let query = db("courses").where({ is_published: true });\n\n    if (opts.category) query = query.where({ category: opts.category });\n    if (opts.level)    query = query.where({ level: opts.level });\n\n    const [courses, [{ count }]] = await Promise.all([\n      query.clone().select("*").limit(opts.limit).offset(offset),\n      query.clone().count("id as count"),\n    ]);\n\n    return { courses, total: Number(count) };\n  }\n\n  async findById(id: string): Promise<Course | null> {\n    return db("courses").where({ id }).first() ?? null;\n  }\n\n  async create(data: CreateCourseDTO & { authorId: string }): Promise<Course> {\n    const [course] = await db("courses").insert(data).returning("*");\n    return course;\n  }\n\n  async update(id: string, data: Partial<Course>): Promise<Course | null> {\n    const [updated] = await db("courses").where({ id }).update(data).returning("*");\n    return updated ?? null;\n  }\n\n  async delete(id: string): Promise<boolean> {\n    const count = await db("courses").where({ id }).delete();\n    return count > 0;\n  }\n}\n\n// ====== services/course.service.ts ======\n// ONLY business logic — no HTTP, no raw SQL\n\nexport class CourseService {\n  constructor(\n    private courseRepo: CourseRepository,\n    private userRepo:   UserRepository,\n    private emailService: EmailService,\n  ) {}\n\n  async getCourses(opts: CoursePaginationOptions) {\n    return this.courseRepo.findAll(opts);\n  }\n\n  async getCourseById(id: string): Promise<Course> {\n    const course = await this.courseRepo.findById(id);\n    if (!course) throw new NotFoundError("Course", id);\n    return course;\n  }\n\n  async createCourse(data: CreateCourseDTO, authorId: string): Promise<Course> {\n    // Business rules:\n    const author = await this.userRepo.findById(authorId);\n    if (!author) throw new NotFoundError("User", authorId);\n    if (!["mentor", "admin"].includes(author.role)) {\n      throw new ForbiddenError("Only mentors and admins can create courses");\n    }\n\n    const existing = await this.courseRepo.findByTitle(data.title);\n    if (existing) throw new ConflictError(`Course "${data.title}" already exists`);\n\n    const course = await this.courseRepo.create({ ...data, authorId });\n\n    // Side effects\n    await this.emailService.sendCourseCreatedNotification(author.email, course);\n\n    return course;\n  }\n\n  async publishCourse(id: string, userId: string): Promise<Course> {\n    const [course, user] = await Promise.all([\n      this.getCourseById(id),\n      this.userRepo.findById(userId),\n    ]);\n\n    if (course.authorId !== userId && user?.role !== "admin") {\n      throw new ForbiddenError("Cannot publish another user''s course");\n    }\n\n    return this.courseRepo.update(id, { publishedAt: new Date() });\n  }\n}\n\n// ====== controllers/course.controller.ts ======\n// ONLY HTTP handling — delegates to service, no business logic\n\nexport class CourseController {\n  constructor(private courseService: CourseService) {}\n\n  getAll = async (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n    try {\n      const { page = "1", limit = "20", category, level } = req.query;\n      const result = await this.courseService.getCourses({\n        page:  Number(page),\n        limit: Math.min(Number(limit), 100),\n        category: category as string,\n        level:    level as string,\n      });\n      res.json({ success: true, data: result });\n    } catch (error) {\n      next(error);\n    }\n  };\n\n  getById = async (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n    try {\n      const course = await this.courseService.getCourseById(req.params.id);\n      res.json({ success: true, data: course });\n    } catch (error) {\n      next(error);\n    }\n  };\n\n  create = async (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n    try {\n      const course = await this.courseService.createCourse(req.body, req.user!.id);\n      res.status(201)\n         .header("Location", `/api/courses/${course.id}`)\n         .json({ success: true, data: course });\n    } catch (error) {\n      next(error);\n    }\n  };\n}\n\n// ====== routes/course.routes.ts ======\nconst repo       = new CourseRepository();\nconst service    = new CourseService(repo, userRepo, emailService);\nconst controller = new CourseController(service);\n\nrouter.get("/",    controller.getAll);\nrouter.get("/:id", controller.getById);\nrouter.post("/",   authenticate, authorize("mentor", "admin"), controller.create);\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the benefit of separating Controllers from Services?**\n> Controllers handle HTTP concerns (parsing request, sending response, HTTP status codes). Services handle business logic. The separation means: (1) Business logic is testable without HTTP (unit test services directly). (2) Services can be reused across REST, GraphQL, CLI, workers. (3) Clear responsibility — change HTTP structure in controllers without touching business logic.\n\n**Q: What is the Repository pattern?**\n> Repository is an abstraction over data access — it hides database-specific code (SQL, ORM queries) behind a clean interface. Benefits: (1) Business logic doesn''t depend on database technology. (2) Easy to swap databases without changing business logic. (3) Easy to mock in tests — just mock the repository interface.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What are the three layers and their responsibilities?\n2. What should NEVER appear in a Service layer?\n3. What should NEVER appear in a Controller layer?\n4. What is the Repository pattern?\n5. Why is layered architecture better than putting everything in route handlers?\n6. What is Dependency Injection?\n7. How does this architecture help with testing?\n8. What is the Data Transfer Object (DTO) pattern?\n9. What is the difference between a Controller and a Service?\n10. What layer should database transactions live in?\n\n---\n\n## 5. Lesson Summary\n\n| Layer | Responsibility | Contains |\n|-------|---------------|----------|\n| Controller | HTTP handling | req/res, validation, status codes |\n| Service | Business logic | Rules, orchestration, side effects |\n| Repository | Data access | SQL/ORM queries, CRUD |\n\nLayered architecture is the foundation of maintainable backends. Separate concerns, test each layer independently, and your codebase will remain manageable as it grows.', 30, 1)
WHERE id = 'l130101';

-- ── TRACK 14: SYSTEM DESIGN ──────────────────────────────

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# System Design Fundamentals — Thinking at Scale\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nSystem design is the process of designing the architecture, components, and data flow of a large-scale software system. It is asked in senior engineering interviews at every major tech company and is the daily work of senior engineers.\n\nFor R-Learn employees: this knowledge helps you understand WHY the systems you work on are built the way they are, and enables you to contribute to architectural decisions.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The System Design Framework\n\n```\nApproach every system design problem in order:\n\n1. Clarify Requirements (5 minutes)\n   - Functional: What features must it have?\n   - Non-functional: Scale, latency, availability, consistency?\n   - Constraints: Traffic, data size, team size?\n   - Out of scope: What are we NOT building?\n\n2. Estimate Scale (3 minutes)\n   - Daily Active Users (DAU)\n   - Requests per second (RPS)\n   - Data storage (GB/TB)\n   - Bandwidth requirements\n\n3. High-Level Design (10 minutes)\n   - Draw boxes: clients, load balancer, servers, databases, caches, CDN\n   - Define API contract\n   - Choose database type\n\n4. Deep Dive into Components (15 minutes)\n   - Focus on most complex/interesting component\n   - Data models\n   - Algorithms\n   - Trade-offs\n\n5. Address Bottlenecks (7 minutes)\n   - Horizontal scaling\n   - Caching strategy\n   - Database sharding/replication\n   - CDN for static assets\n```\n\n## 3. Back-of-Envelope Estimation\n\n```\nMemory Numbers:\n  1 char  = 1 byte\n  1 KB    = 10^3 bytes   (1,024)\n  1 MB    = 10^6 bytes   (1,048,576)\n  1 GB    = 10^9 bytes   (1,073,741,824)\n  1 TB    = 10^12 bytes\n  1 PB    = 10^15 bytes\n\nTime Numbers:\n  1ms  = millisecond  (10^-3 s)\n  1μs  = microsecond  (10^-6 s)\n  1ns  = nanosecond   (10^-9 s)\n\n  L1 cache access:    ~0.5ns\n  RAM access:         ~100ns\n  SSD random read:    ~100μs\n  HDD random read:    ~10ms\n  Same datacenter:    ~0.5ms\n  Cross-continent:    ~150ms\n\nTraffic Estimation:\n  Twitter: 500M tweets/day\n  = 500M / 86400 ≈ 6,000 tweets/second\n  Peak traffic ≈ 3× average ≈ 18,000 TPS\n\n  Storage per tweet: 280 chars text + metadata ≈ 300 bytes\n  Daily storage: 500M × 300 bytes = 150 GB/day\n  5-year storage: 150 GB × 365 × 5 = ~270 TB\n```\n\n## 4. Key Components\n\n```\nLOAD BALANCER\n  Distributes traffic across multiple servers\n  Algorithms: Round Robin, Least Connections, IP Hash\n  Types: L4 (TCP), L7 (HTTP — content-aware)\n  Examples: Nginx, AWS ALB, Cloudflare\n\nCDN (Content Delivery Network)\n  Caches static assets at edge servers near users\n  Reduces latency for images, CSS, JS, videos\n  Examples: Cloudflare, AWS CloudFront, Fastly\n\nCACHE\n  In-memory key-value store for fast reads\n  Reduces database load\n  Types: Application cache (Redis), CDN cache, Browser cache\n  Eviction: LRU, LFU, TTL-based\n\nDATABASE\n  SQL (PostgreSQL, MySQL): ACID, relational, strong consistency\n  NoSQL (MongoDB): Flexible schema, horizontal scaling\n  Key-Value (Redis, DynamoDB): Fast, simple lookups\n  Time-Series (InfluxDB): Metrics, logs\n  Full-Text Search (Elasticsearch): Complex queries\n\nMESSAGE QUEUE\n  Async communication between services\n  Decouples producers and consumers\n  Examples: Kafka, RabbitMQ, AWS SQS\n  Use for: email sending, notifications, async jobs\n```\n\n## 5. URL Shortener Design Example\n\n```\nRequirements:\n  - Shorten a URL: POST /shorten → short code\n  - Redirect: GET /{code} → 301 to original URL\n  - 100M URLs stored\n  - 10M requests/day → 100 req/sec average, 300 peak\n\nEstimation:\n  - Short code: 7 chars (62^7 = 3.5T combinations — plenty)\n  - Storage per entry: ~500 bytes → 100M × 500 = 50 GB\n\nHigh-Level Design:\n  Client → CDN → Load Balancer → App Servers → PostgreSQL\n                                             → Redis Cache\n\nData Model:\n  CREATE TABLE short_urls (\n    id         SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    code       VARCHAR(7) UNIQUE NOT NULL,\n    long_url   TEXT NOT NULL,\n    created_at TIMESTAMPTZ DEFAULT NOW(),\n    expires_at TIMESTAMPTZ,\n    clicks     INTEGER DEFAULT 0\n  );\n  CREATE INDEX idx_code ON short_urls(code);\n\nAlgorithm for generating short codes:\n  Option 1: Hash (MD5/SHA256 of long URL, take first 7 chars)\n    Pro: Deterministic, same URL → same code\n    Con: Collisions possible\n  Option 2: Base62(auto-increment ID)\n    Pro: No collisions, simple\n    Con: Predictable/sequential codes\n  Option 3: Random 7-char base62\n    Pro: Unpredictable\n    Con: Need uniqueness check\n\nCaching:\n  Redis: code → long_url, TTL 24 hours\n  Cache hit rate ~80% for popular links\n  Read throughput: Redis handles 100K+ reads/sec\n\nScaling:\n  - Add more app servers (horizontal scaling)\n  - Database read replica for GET requests\n  - Redis cache hit rate >80% — most reads never hit DB\n  - CDN caches 301 responses for popular codes\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between vertical and horizontal scaling?**\n> Vertical scaling: make one server bigger (more CPU, RAM). Simple but has limits. Expensive. Horizontal scaling: add more servers and distribute load. Requires stateless design, load balancer, shared state (Redis). Almost unlimited scale. Preferred for production systems.\n\n**Q: What is the CAP theorem?**\n> A distributed system can guarantee at most two of: Consistency (all nodes see same data), Availability (system always responds), Partition Tolerance (works despite network failures). Network partitions are unavoidable, so systems choose CP (consistent + partition-tolerant, may be unavailable) or AP (available + partition-tolerant, may be inconsistent). PostgreSQL is CP; DynamoDB is AP.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What are the steps of the system design framework?\n2. What does a load balancer do?\n3. What is horizontal vs vertical scaling?\n4. What is a CDN used for?\n5. What is the CAP theorem?\n6. What types of databases exist and when to use each?\n7. What is back-of-envelope estimation?\n8. What is a message queue used for?\n9. What is cache eviction?\n10. What is the difference between synchronous and asynchronous communication?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Component | Purpose |\n|-----------|--------|\n| Load Balancer | Distribute traffic across servers |\n| CDN | Cache static assets at edge |\n| Cache (Redis) | Fast in-memory data store |\n| SQL Database | Relational, ACID, complex queries |\n| NoSQL Database | Flexible, scalable |\n| Message Queue | Async, decoupled communication |\n| Horizontal scaling | Add more servers |\n\nSystem design is the skill that separates senior engineers. Think in components, estimate at scale, and always consider trade-offs. The best design is the simplest one that meets the requirements.', 30, 1)
WHERE id = 'l140101';
